Gabinius, tri- bune in 139 Β. c., and introduced into elections voting by ballot, i. e. by writing the name of the candidate on a ticket or tablet. — Cas- sia: this law was carried by L. Cassius Longinus Ravilla, tribune in 137 Β. c., and extended the ballot to the juries in the criminal courts. Cassius was afterwards a judge and for his severity called scopulus reorum ; he was the author of the saying ‘cui b0n0?' (i. e. who gains by it? viz. the offence). The lex tabellaria of Carbo introduced the ballot for voting on laws proposed to the comitia. His law is com- monly placed in 131 B. c., but there is no direct evidence for the date and it may have been several years later. — populum . .. multitu- dinis: the change seems made merely for the sake of variety.
